9 An Act relating to crimes and punishments; amending
21 O.S. 2021, Section 425, as amended by Section 370,
10 Chapter 486, O.S.L. 2025 (21 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section
425), which relates to the pattern of criminal
11 offenses; modifying elements of certain unlawful act;
expanding scope of certain defined term; amending 21
12 O.S. 2021, Section 843.4, as amended by Section 194,
Chapter 486, O.S.L. 2025 (21 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section
13 843.4), which relates to the exploitation of elderly
or disabled persons; making certain acts unlawful;
14 providing penalties; defining terms; amending 21 O.S.
2021, Section 1533.1, as amended by Section 423,
15 Chapter 486, O.S.L. 2025 (21 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section
1533.1), which relates to identity theft; expanding
16 scope of crime to include specific identification
information; providing elements for aggravated
17 identity theft; making certain acts unlawful;
providing penalties for subsequent convictions;
18 providing penalties for aggravated identity theft;
authorizing the use of identity theft task force
19 officers; providing for the dissemination of certain
identification information; defining terms; and
20 providing an effective date.
21
22 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
23
24
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - HB3244 SFLR Page 1
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 21 O.S. 2021, Section 425, as
2 amended by Section 370, Chapter 486, O.S.L. 2025 (21 O.S. Supp.
3 2025, Section 425), is amended to read as follows:
4 Section 425. A. Any person who engages in a pattern of
5 criminal offenses in:
6 1. In two or more counties in this state;
7 2. In two or more municipalities in this state;
8 3. In an unincorporated portion of a county and in a
9 municipality within the same county;
10 4. When one of the offenses was committed outside this state
11 and the other was committed within this state;
12 5. In circumstances when the initial act was committed online
13 through cyberspace, by a computer application, social media,
14 artificial intelligence, or by a cellular network, regardless of
15 location, and an additional act was committed inside this state; or
16 who
17 6. Who attempts or conspires with others to engage in a pattern
18 of criminal offenses,
19 shall, upon conviction, be guilty of a Class D1 felony offense
20 punishable by imprisonment as provided for in subsections B through
21 F of Section 20N of this title, or by a fine in an amount not more
22 than Twenty-five Thousand Dollars ($25,000.00), or by both such fine
23 and imprisonment. Such punishment shall be in addition to any
24
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - HB3244 SFLR Page 2
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 pena lty imposed for any offense involved in the pattern of criminal
2 offenses. Double jeopardy shall attach upon conviction.
3 B. For purposes of this act section, "pattern of criminal
4 offenses" means:
5 1. Two or more criminal offenses are committed that are part of
6 the same plan, scheme, or adventure; or
7 2. A sequence of two or more of the same criminal offenses are
8 committed and are not separated by an interval of more than thirty
9 (30) days between the first and second offense, the second and
10 third, and so on; or
11 3. Two or more criminal offenses are committed, each proceeding
12 from or having as an antecedent element a single prior incident or
13 pattern of fraud, robbery, burglary, theft, identity theft, receipt
14 of stolen property, false personation, false pretenses, obtaining
15 property by trick or deception, taking a credit or debit card
16 without consent, organized retail theft, or the making, transferring
17 or receiving of a false or fraudulent identification card.
18 C. Jurisdiction and venue for a pattern of criminal offenses
19 occurring in multiple counties in this state shall be determined as
20 provided in Section 1 125.1 of this act Title 22 of the Oklahoma
21 Statutes.
22 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY 21 O.S. 2021, Section 843.4, as
23 amended by Section 194, Chapter 486, O.S.L. 2025 (21 O.S. Supp.
24 2025, Section 843.4), is amended to read as follows:
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - HB3244 SFLR Page 3
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 Section 843.4. A. As used in this section, "exploitation of an
2 elderly person or disabled adult" means:
3 1. Knowingly, by deception or intimidation, obtaining or using,
4 or endeavoring to obtain or use, an elderly person's or disabled
5 adult's funds, assets, or property with the intent to temporarily or
6 permanently deprive the elderly person or disabled adult of the use,
7 benefit, or possession of the funds, assets, or property, or to
8 benefit someone other than the elderly person or disabled adult, by
9 a person who:
10 a. stands in a position of trust and confidence with the
11 elderly person or disabled adult, or
12 b. has a business relationship with the elderly person or
13 disabled adult,; or
14 2. Obtaining or using, endeavoring to obtain or use, or
15 conspiring with another to obtain or use an elderly person's or
16 disabled adult's funds, assets, or property with the intent to
17 temporarily or permanently deprive the elderly person or disabled
18 adult of the use, benefit, or possession of the funds, assets, or
19 property, or to benefit someone other than the elderly person or
20 disabled adult, by a person who knows or reasonably should know that
21 the elderly person or disabled adult lacks the capacity to consent.
22 B. 1. If the funds, assets, or property involved in the
23 exploitation of the elderly person or disabled adult are valued at
24 One Hundred Thousand Dollars ($100,000.00) or more, the violator
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - HB3244 SFLR Page 4
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 comm its a Class C1 felony offense punishable by imprisonment as
2 provided for in subsections B through E of Section 20L of this
3 title, and by a fine in an amount not exceeding Ten Thousand Dollars
4 ($10,000.00).
5 2. If the funds, assets, or property involved in the
6 exploitation of the elderly person or disabled adult are valued at
7 less than One Hundred Thousand Dollars ($100,000.00), the violator
8 commits a Class C2 felony offense punishable by imprisonment as
9 provided for in subsections B through F of Section 20M of this title
10 and by a fine in an amount not exceeding Ten Thousand Dollars
11 ($10,000.00).
12 C. It shall be unlawful for a person to use coercion,
13 deception, enticement, intimidation, bartering, recruiting, or other
14 means, to exploit another who has a mental illness, is vulnerable,
15 homeless, intellectually or developmentally disabled, elderly, a
16 user of drugs or alcohol, a minor, or whose legal status in this
17 country may be unlawful, to engage in any crime. Any person
18 convicted of violating the provisions of this section shall be
19 guilty of a felony, punishable by imprisonment in the custody of the
20 Department of Corrections for a term not exceeding ten (10) years,
21 or by a fine not exceeding Ten Thousand Dollars ($10,000.00), or by
22 both such fine and imprisonment.
23 D. It shall be unlawful for a person to engage in a pattern of
24 exploitation by coercion, deception, enticement, intimidation,
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - HB3244 SFLR Page 5
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 bart ering, recruiting, or other means, of another who has a mental
2 illness, is vulnerable, homeless, intellectually or developmentally
3 disabled, elderly, a user of drugs or alcohol, a minor, or whose
4 legal status in this country may be unlawful, to engage in any
5 crime.
6 1. A pattern of exploitation shall be established if:
7 a. a person has a previous conviction under any of the
8 provisions of this section,
9 b. a person has a previous conviction for contributing to
10 the delinquency of a minor pursuant to Section 856 of
11 this title,
12 c. a person has a previous conviction for abuse, neglect,
13 exploitation, or sexual abuse of a child pursuant to
14 Section 843.5 of this title, or
15 d. a person participated in circumstances in which the
16 exploited person committed criminal acts in violation
17 of Section 425 of this title.
18 2. Any person who violates the provisions of this subsection
19 shall be guilty of a felony, punishable by imprisonment in the
20 custody of the Department of Corrections for a term not exceeding
21 twenty (20) years, or by a fine not exceeding Twenty Thousand
22 Dollars ($20,000.00), or by both such fine and imprisonment.
23 E. For purposes of this section, "elderly person":
24
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - HB3244 SFLR Page 6
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 1. "Elderly person" means any person sixty-two (62) years of
2 age or older;
3 2. "Exploited" means any person who is deceived, enticed,
4 intimidated, recruited, bartered with, or in any other way
5 convinced, lured, or manipulated into engaging in any crime;
6 3. "Homeless individual" shall have the same meaning as such
7 term is defined in paragraph 2 of subsection A of Section 2900.1 of
8 Title 74 of the Oklahoma Statutes;
9 4. "Mental illness" shall have the same meaning as such term is
10 defined in Section 1-103 of Title 43A of the Oklahoma Statutes; and
11 5. "Minor" means any person under twenty-one (21) years of age.
